## **🧠 System-on-Chip (SoC) Overview**

A **System-on-Chip (SoC)** integrates **processor, memory, interfaces, and analog/digital IPs** onto a **single silicon chip**, forming a compact, high-performance computing system.

### **🔍 Advantages**

| Feature | Benefit |
| ----- | ----- |
| 🧩 Tiny & Portable | Used in smartphones, IoT, wearables |
| ⚡ Energy Efficient | Optimized for low-power operation |
| 🚀 High Performance | Faster data transfer within chip |
| 💰 Cost-Effective | Fewer components, simpler PCB design |

---

## **🏗️ SoC Building Blocks**

| Component | Function |
| ----- | ----- |
| CPU | Executes program instructions |
| Memory | Stores code & data |
| I/O | Interfaces with external devices |
| GPU | Graphics & parallel computation |
| DSP | Signal processing (audio/image) |
| Power Management | Controls energy & thermal limits |
| Connectivity | Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, LTE, etc. |

**Analogy:** A SoC is like a **city** —  
 Mayor (CPU), Libraries (Memory), Roads (I/O), Art Galleries (GPU), Concert Halls (DSP), Power Stations (Power Mgmt), Airports (Connectivity).

---

## **🏷️ Types of SoCs**

| Type | Description | Example Use |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Microcontroller SoC | Low-power, simple control | IoT sensors |
| Microprocessor SoC | Full OS support | Smartphones |
| ASIC SoC | Custom-designed | AI accelerators, automotive chips |

## **🧩 VSDBabySoC – Minimal RISC-V SoC on Sky130**

**Objective:** Demonstrate an educational open-source SoC design.

### **🔬 Core Components**

| Block | Description |
| ----- | ----- |
| 🧠 RVMYTH Core | RISC-V CPU generating data (r17) |
| ⏱️ PLL | Generates stable system clock |
| 🎚️ DAC | Converts digital r17 to analog voltage output![][image2] |

## **⚙️ Simulation Flow**

### **🧱 Pre-Synthesis Simulation**

`iverilog -o output/pre_synth_sim/pre_synth_sim.out \`  
  `-DPRE_SYNTH_SIM \`  
  `-I src/include -I src/module \`  
  `src/module/testbench.v`

`cd output/pre_synth_sim`  
`./pre_synth_sim.out`

### **View Results in GTKWave:**

`gtkwave output/pre_synth_sim/pre_synth_sim.vcd![][image3]`

### **🔍 Key Signals**

* `clk` – PLL output clock

* `reset` – System reset

* `RV_TO_DAC[9:0]` – Data from CPU

* `DAC_OUT` – Analog voltage output

---

## **🧮 DAC Output Calculation**

VOUT=r171023×VREFSPANV\_{OUT} \= \\frac{r17}{1023} \\times V\_{REFSPAN}VOUT​=1023r17​×VREFSPAN​

For VREFSPAN=1.0VV\_{REFSPAN} \= 1.0VVREFSPAN​=1.0V:

| r17 | Output Voltage (V) |
| ----- | ----- |
| 903 | 0.882 |
| 946 | 0.925 |

---

## **🕹️ RISC-V Program Flow**

| \# | Instruction | Purpose |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| 0 | ADDI r9, r0, 1 | Step size |
| 3 | ADDI r17, r0, 0 | Initialize DAC input |
| 4 | ADD r17, r17, r11 | Accumulate |
| 6 | BNE r11, r10, \-4 | Loop until limit |
| 12 | BEQ r0, r0, ... | Halt loop |

🌀 **Waveform:** DAC output oscillates as the CPU iterates — visible in GTKWave’s *Analog Step* mode.
